00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:25.290
And it's long and I don't really have any
simple answers for that. But I think that

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:33.950
with, what the right has done over the past
40 years is to move the center in their direction.

00:43:33.950 --> 00:43:39.950
So that, I mean, Barack Obama. Not only did
he choose a guy from the financial industry,

00:43:39.950 --> 00:43:45.470
William Daley, but he chose a guy who didn't
support his healthcare program; the most important,

00:43:45.470 --> 00:43:48.930
the thing he should be proudest of, the thing
he put most of his time in, the thing that

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:55.840
his presidency will rise and fall on in terms
of what are his signal accomplishments.

00:43:55.840 --> 00:44:01.630
He picked a guy who was against all that.
And he did it because the narrative demanded

00:44:01.630 --> 00:44:06.450
that he move to the center, that he be more
friendly to business. Now remember, business

00:44:06.450 --> 00:44:11.839
got 90 percent of what it wanted out of the
financial bill. They defined the shape of

00:44:11.839 --> 00:44:16.309
the healthcare bill. They defeated cap in
trade. And yet Obama is perceived as being

00:44:16.309 --> 00:44:17.309
anti-business.

00:44:17.309 --> 00:44:22.700
In fact, I would say, I know numbers about
30 percent of people consider Obama to be

00:44:22.700 --> 00:44:27.880
a socialist, as if we somehow elected a Socialist
to be our President. This is, this is the

00:44:27.880 --> 00:44:35.750
power of the right-wing media and conservative
institutions who began this process in the

00:44:35.750 --> 00:44:41.309
early 1970s to redefine the playing field
in American politics, and they have succeeded.

00:44:41.309 --> 00:44:47.661
And before anything could really be accomplished
on the kinds of issues that you raise, the

00:44:47.661 --> 00:44:54.089
other side needs to organize itself for a
long-term battle of ideas in the same way.

00:44:54.089 --> 00:44:58.170
And those investments need to be made. Most
of the funders in the Democratic Party now

00:44:58.170 --> 00:45:07.970
are the kinds of people who have founded Google
and Silicon Valley institutions, entrepreneurs.

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:10.170
And I have nothing at all against entrepreneurs.

00:45:10.170 --> 00:45:18.200
They're very important. Where would we be
without them? But they want results. They

00:45:18.200 --> 00:45:23.200
want quarterly results or maybe annual results
at best. And these investments take decades

00:45:23.200 --> 00:45:26.480
and the Republicans have spent, they've wasted
a lot of money, they're conservatives. They've

00:45:26.480 --> 00:45:32.619
wasted a lot of money building their structures
because it’s hard to know what will work.

00:45:32.619 --> 00:45:34.140
It's impossible to know what will work and
you gotta give things time.

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:41.620
And when you think about it from an entrepreneurial
standpoint, an awful lot of angel money goes

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:47.609
out the window over time. But the one thing
that sticks pays for everything else. And

00:45:47.609 --> 00:45:53.250
yet, in politics, this money is expected to
show results overnight and so that groups

00:45:53.250 --> 00:46:00.020
like the Democracy Alliance, which is all
these Democratic billionaires and millionaires,

00:46:00.020 --> 00:46:05.020
who've committed a certain number, 800,000
dollars I think, each over a period of, I

00:46:05.020 --> 00:46:09.650
don't know exactly what the period is, but
a lot of money.

00:46:09.650 --> 00:46:15.660
They have a structure that demands all kinds
of benchmarks be met that are just not that

00:46:15.660 --> 00:46:20.890
appropriate to business, but not appropriate
to the world of ideas. And so, the first thing

00:46:20.890 --> 00:46:26.460
I would ask for would be patient investing
in ideas. That would be number one. And then

00:46:26.460 --> 00:46:35.740
number two, I would ask for less caution,
less fear, to give voice to one's ideas. That

00:46:35.740 --> 00:46:41.740
not, just to, you can take back what you said
if it turns out you were wrong. But there's

00:46:41.740 --> 00:46:44.410
so much nervousness about being the target.

00:46:44.410 --> 00:46:49.440
I mean, when the Gulf War happened, Bill O'Reilly
put my picture up on the television screen

00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:56.910
as a mug shot 'cause I opposed the Gulf War.
Like, I was supposed to, I was guilty of something,

00:46:56.910 --> 00:47:02.810
of having a difference of opinion with FOX
News. And I was fine with that because I don't

00:47:02.810 --> 00:47:07.610
make my living on whether or not FOX News
likes me. And none of my friends were gonna

00:47:07.610 --> 00:47:08.610
stop being friends with me and I was gonna
keep getting invited to parties.

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:15.130
Like, it didn't hurt me in any way and actually,
I enjoyed it. But if you're in, if you're

00:47:15.130 --> 00:47:23.960
not, if you're in the real world, it can be
really scary. It can be a real problem for

00:47:23.960 --> 00:47:30.750
you, particularly as they get meaner and meaner
and occasionally, people get shot or get threatened.

00:47:30.750 --> 00:47:33.650
One of my colleagues at CUNY is now the target
of a Glenn Beck attack. That is quite scary.

00:47:33.650 --> 00:47:38.140
The New York Times wrote an article about
it this week, about how she's getting death

00:47:38.140 --> 00:47:39.140
threats and Beck is using really incendiary
language about her.

00:47:39.140 --> 00:47:44.470
And she's just writing articles about politics.
So we need a little bit more courage and we

00:47:44.470 --> 00:47:51.350
need a longer term investment. And we need
to, we need to ape their ability to discipline

00:47:51.350 --> 00:47:56.170
themselves. That would be, I guess, the three
broad categories. Thank you.

